, scripts portrayed date and marital rape and paid greater attention to the trial process, reflecting legal reformers' concerns. While previous studies have examined one series or genre, Cuklanz examines programs as dissimilar as Barney Miller, Dallas, The Cosby Show, and Quincy. She outlines the "basic plot" for rape episodes, then traces the historical development of rape themes. In each chapter she includes close analyses of episodes that add depth to findings derived from scripts and taped episodes. Rape on Prime Time provides important insight into the social construction of rape in mainstream mass media since the inception of rape law reform in 1974.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFeminist theory. 0aRape in mass media. 0aSex in mass media. 0aWomenvCrimes against. 0aWomenxCrimes against. 4aMedia Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aCultural Studies.  aFilm Studies.  aGender Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedia Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220400140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812204001423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812204001/original  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041361-8  Penn Press eBook Package Social Sciences  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_